  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!-->\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nNFS server got restarted and caused the nfs mounts to be stale.  Pod deletion hung with:\r\n```\r\nError: \"error cleaning subPath mounts for volume \\\"nfs-content\\\": error reading /var/lib/kubelet/pods/redacted/volume-subpaths/nfs-content/redacted: lstat /var/lib/kubelet/pods/redacted/volume-subpaths/nfs-content/redacted/2: stale NFS file handle\"\r\n```\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nI think the [subpath directory traversing](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/v1.9.7/pkg/util/mount/mount_linux.go#L780) needs to check for a [stale mount](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/v1.9.7/pkg/volume/util/util.go#L184)\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nI have not been able to repro the stale nfs mount.  These are the steps I tried:\r\n1. start a nfs-server using https://github.com/kubernetes/examples/tree/master/staging/volumes/nfs\r\n2. create a pod using subpath with nfs. write data into the subpath.\r\n3. restart the nfs-server pod\r\n4. Write more data into the subpath\r\n5. delete pod\r\n\r\nIn my test, the nfs mount is able to recover from the nfs server restarting.  Maybe my next attempt to repro should bring the nfs server down for longer.\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): 1.9.7\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration: GKE\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release): COS\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Others:\r\n\r\n<!-- DO NOT EDIT BELOW THIS LINE -->\r\n/kind bug",
